Opinion
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_Ie40c3cf5e6e411eabea4f0dc9fb69}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_Ie40c3cf5e6e411eabea4f0dc9fb69}
\par 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=h&pubNum=176284&cite=0141887401&originatingDoc=I1101afc40dc211d99830b5efa1ded32a&refType=RQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
SCHWARTZ
}}}
\sa200 
\sb200 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
, Chief Judge.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_Ie40c3cf7e6e411eabea4f0dc9fb69}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_Ie40c3cf7e6e411eabea4f0dc9fb69}
\par 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The trial court upheld the issuance of a building permit for a very substantial expansion of a motel on Lower Matecumbe Key, Monroe County. We reverse the judgment upon the holding that the existing motel, originally constructed in 1956, constituted a nonconforming use in its present district which, under the general law and the specific terms of Monroe County\rquote s zoning ordinance,
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_B00111990015534_ID0EVMAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_B00111990015534_ID0EVMAC_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_B00111990015534_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
1
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 may not be lawfully enlarged or expanded.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_hn_anchor_F11990015534_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf31 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[1]
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The operative facts are entirely undisputed. The appellee Popplewell\rquote s property was constructed in 1956 as a five-unit cabin-type motel. At that time, Monroe County had yet to enact its first zoning ordinance, which did not come into effect until 1960. Because the surrounding land on both sides of the motel is single-family residential\u8212\'3fthe appellant Dowd is a next door neighbor\u8212\'3fboth that area and the property in question were zoned RU\u8211\'3f1, single-family residential, soon thereafter.
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_B00221990015534_ID0E2OAC_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_B00221990015534_ID0E2OAC_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_B00221990015534_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
2
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 The motel usage, although plainly not permitted in RU\u8211\'3f1, was \u8220\'3fgrandfathered\u8221\'3f in as a pre-existing non-conforming use. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=0281455019&pubNum=0114556&originatingDoc=I1101afc40dc211d99830b5efa1ded32a&refType=TS&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
7 Fla.Jur.2d Building, Zoning, and Land Controls \u167\'3f 131 (1978)
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. Motels which were constructed subsequent to 1960 were ordinarily placed in RU\u8211\'3f3 district which included that use along with hotels, apartment houses and the like. In 1973, the county in effect divided the RU\u8211\'3f3 zone into two separate categories. One was RU\u8211\'3f7, a so-called residential tourist district. The provision which created it, section 19\u8211\'3f202, Monroe County Code (1985), upon which the appellees entirely rely, provided as follows:
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
This district is intended to provide an area for accommodations oriented to the transient and resort trade, with a residential character, and preserving and protecting the amenities of a living environment.
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 All existing hotels, 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
motels,
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 tourist accommodations, marinas and resorts 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
conforming to all the requirements of the district in which it is located
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
 prior to the adoption of Ordinance No. 1\u8211\'3f1973 shall be considered to conform to this RU\u8211\'3f7 district and shall be treated as though they were in an RU\u8211\'3f7 district for the purposes of enforcing and administering this ordinance. [emphasis supplied]
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
When Popplewell sought to expand his motel into a thirty unit structure in 1985,
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_B00331990015534_ID0EYBAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_B00331990015534_ID0EYBAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_B00331990015534_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
3
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Dowd objected on the ground that the motel was a non-conforming use which could not be enlarged under either the Monroe County Code
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_B00441990015534_ID0E6BAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_B00441990015534_ID0E6BAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_B00441990015534_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
4
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 or the general law. 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://1.next.westlaw.com/Link/RelatedInformation/Flag?documentGuid=I0a146f530d2611d9821e9512eb7d7b26&transitionType=InlineKeyCiteFlags&originationContext=docHeaderFlag&Rank=0&ppcid=5c1ffa3fc41340be973de0931d2f376c&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\*\shppict {\pict \pngblip \picw16 \pich16 \picwgoal255 \pichgoal255 }}}}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_735_65_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_735_65_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*65
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1966114977&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I1101afc40dc211d99830b5efa1ded32a&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Bixler 
}
}
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
v. Pierson,
}
}
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 188 So.2d 681 (Fla. 4th DCA 1966)
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. Popplewell, however, argued successfully to the Monroe Building & Zoning Department, the County Board of Adjustments, the County Commission and the Circuit Court
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_B00551990015534_ID0EHDAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_B00551990015534_ID0EHDAE_1}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_B00551990015534_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
5
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 that, by virtue of section 19\u8211\'3f202, the motel was lawfully within RU\u8211\'3f7, the appropriate district for motel use, and thus could be permissibly expanded. We find otherwise.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_hn_anchor_F21990015534_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf31 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[2]
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Both sides agree that the issue before us is entirely determined by whether the motel is now being used in conformance with the applicable terms of the Monroe County Zoning Code. This question, in turn, depends on whether it is presently located in the RU\u8211\'3f7 district which permits a motel usage and a subsequent expansion. Last on the logical ladder, the motel could only fall within RU\u8211\'3f7 if section 19\u8211\'3f202 applies. In our view, it clearly does not.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Section 19\u8211\'3f202 permits the treatment of existing motels as if they were in an RU\u8211\'3f7 district, only when that structure \u8220\'3fconform[s] to all the requirements of the district in which it is located.\u8221\'3f But the present structure did not so conform when section 19\u8211\'3f292 was enacted and has not done so since. Instead, it was no more than a grandfathered 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
non
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 -conforming use in the RU\u8211\'3f1 district in which it has been located\u8212\'3fwithout amendment or interruption\u8212\'3fsince the first Monroe County zoning ordinance was enacted. There is no question that motel use is not permitted in an RU\u8211\'3f1 district and that the motel\rquote s prior construction and use is the only reason why it is permitted to remain there. By definition of section 19.5, Monroe County Code (1973) (Non-conforming use of a building is \u8220\'3f[t]he use of any building other than a use specifically permitted in the district in which the building is located.\u8221\'3f), and the self-evident meaning of the words, a non-conforming use 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
cannot
}
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u8220\'3fconform\u8221\'3f to the district in which it is located, so as to render section 19\u8211\'3f202 applicable to the appellee\rquote s property. 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://1.next.westlaw.com/Link/RelatedInformation/Flag?documentGuid=Ic04c4d84ec5d11d9bf60c1d57ebc853e&transitionType=InlineKeyCiteFlags&originationContext=docHeaderFlag&Rank=0&ppcid=5c1ffa3fc41340be973de0931d2f376c&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\*\shppict {\pict \pngblip \picw16 \pich16 \picwgoal255 \pichgoal255 }}}}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1972132442&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=I1101afc40dc211d99830b5efa1ded32a&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_713_777&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_713_777" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
City of Univ. Park v. Benners,
}
}
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 485 S.W.2d 773, 777 (Tex.1972)
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (nonconforming use is use which existed legally when zoning restriction became effective and has continued to exist), appeal dismissed, 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1973243279&pubNum=708&originatingDoc=I1101afc40dc211d99830b5efa1ded32a&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
411 U.S. 901, 93 S.Ct. 1530, 36 L.Ed.2d 191 (1973)
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
; 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://1.next.westlaw.com/Link/RelatedInformation/Flag?documentGuid=Ia1cc1340ec5d11d98ac8f235252e36df&transitionType=InlineKeyCiteFlags&originationContext=docHeaderFlag&Rank=0&ppcid=5c1ffa3fc41340be973de0931d2f376c&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\*\shppict {\pict \pngblip \picw16 \pich16 \picwgoal255 \pichgoal255 }}}}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1965128974&pubNum=713&originatingDoc=I1101afc40dc211d99830b5efa1ded32a&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_713_594&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_713_594" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Franklin Planning and Zoning Comm\rquote n v. Simpson County Lumber Co.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 394 S.W.2d 593, 594 (Ky.1965)
}}}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (non-conforming use is one which does not conform to the classification provided for); 
}
{\b0 \cf25 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
